He said: ‘You’re making the World Cup sound like the Sherpa Vans Trophy. The World Cup’s the World Cup, it’s hardly a tin-pot competition. The Premier League will be disrupted for a year, every 24 or 28 years, for a continent to have a World Cup. We’ve got to get over it. Football’s a world game.’

Neville added that it was ‘shoddy’ that the decision to move the tournament ‘has taken so long and been a shambles of a process. But I’ve been to the Middle East a number of times and they deserve a World Cup. FIFA have now got to the right place, to make allowances for a continent to host a World Cup in normal heat.’

A switch to November and December 2022 had been virtually inevitable because FIFA’s task force, headed by Asia confederation head Sheik Salman bin Ebrahim Al-Khalifa of Bahrain, had little room for manoeuvre. 

